I started the month by porting the Anouncements section from Raw HTML to Markdown, for which I wrote a small python script that parses all the content in this news.rdf file, inherited from the old site, and creates several markdown post files that will be processed by the list and single templates of the aether-sass theme into the new section.
 To see the full python script, click here import re text_file = open(&#34;./news.rdf&#34;, &#34;r&#34;) data = text_file.read() titles = re.findall(&#39;&lt;title&gt;(.*)&lt;/title&gt;&#39;, data) dates = re.findall(&#39;&lt;date&gt;(.*)&lt;/date&gt;&#39;, data) fullstories = re.findall(&#39;&lt;fullstory&gt;(.*)&lt;/fullstory&gt;&#39;, data) i=0; mes=0; dia =0 for i in range(len(dates)): a√±o = dates[i].split(&#39; &#39;)[2] day = dates[i].split(&#39; &#39;)[1].replace(&#39;,&#39;,&#39;&#39;) if day == &#39;1&#39;: dia = &#39;01&#39; elif day == &#39;2&#39;: dia = &#39;02&#39; elif day == &#39;3&#39;: dia = &#39;03&#39; elif day == &#39;4&#39;: dia = &#39;04&#39; elif day == &#39;5&#39;: dia = &#39;05&#39; elif day == &#39;6&#39;: dia = &#39;06&#39; elif day == &#39;7&#39;: dia = &#39;07&#39; elif day == &#39;8&#39;: dia = &#39;08&#39; elif day == &#39;9&#39;: dia = &#39;09&#39; else: dia = day month = dates[i].split(&#39; &#39;)[0] if month == &#39;January&#39;: mes = &#39;01&#39; elif month == &#39;February&#39;: mes = &#39;02&#39; elif month == &#39;March&#39;: mes = &#39;03&#39; elif month == &#39;April&#39;: mes = &#39;04&#39; elif month == &#39;May&#39;: mes = &#39;05&#39; elif month == &#39;June&#39;: mes = &#39;06&#39; elif month == &#39;July&#39;: mes = &#39;07&#39; elif month == &#39;August&#39;: mes = &#39;08&#39; elif month == &#39;September&#39;: mes = &#39;09&#39; elif month == &#39;October&#39;: mes = &#39;10&#39; elif month == &#39;November&#39;: mes = &#39;11&#39; elif month == &#39;December&#39;: mes = &#39;12&#39; elif month == &#39;December&#39;: mes = &#39;12&#39; elif month == &#39;Jul&#39;: mes = &#39;07&#39; elif month == &#39;Apr&#39;: mes = &#39;04&#39; elif month == &#39;Jan&#39;: mes = &#39;01&#39; elif month == &#39;Nov&#39;: mes = &#39;11&#39; elif month == &#39;Aug&#39;: mes = &#39;08&#39; fecha = str(a√±o)+&#39;-&#39;+str(mes)+&#39;-&#39;+str(dia) filetoopen = str(titles[i].replace(&#39;,&#39;,&#39;&#39;).replace(&#39; &#39;,&#39;_&#39;)+&#39;.md&#39;) f = open(filetoopen, &#34;a&#34;) f.write(&#39;---
date: &#39;+fecha+&#39;
title: &#39;+titles[i]+&#39;
---
&#39;+fullstories[i]) #f.close()  Then, I configured the project to use the aforementioned aether-sass (KDE&rsquo;s HUGO standard theme) as a Go module, as Git submodules are less desirable. Next, I added a FAQ section, which was easy since most questions had been removed from the FAQ in a recent cleanup. For this, I used the &lt;/details&gt; and &lt;/summary&gt; HTML labels, which I didnt know about and which seem super cool to me. This was, also, the first time I experienced how a HUGO template works! Yay!
  I improved the News section using HUGO&rsquo;s list.html and a python script    And added the FAQ using &lt;details&gt; and &lt;summary&gt;   Finally, I added the new /download and /build-it pages, as well as a new index, using a mixture of HUGO markdown and raw html templates. You can see some screenshots below:
  The download section helps you find the availaible download options.    And the Build It section shows how to build from source    details { border: 1px solid #5850ec; border-radius: 10px; padding: .5rem .5rem 0; } summary { margin: -.5rem -.5rem 0; padding: .5rem; } summary:hover { font-weight: bold; } details[open] { padding: .5rem; } details[open] summary { border-bottom: 1px solid #aaa; margin-bottom: .5rem; font-weight: bold; }
